I came from design so I decided to leverage that and try go strong into creative development (as others have mentioned, find a niche). I built a portfolio to showcase that. I sent a looooot of resumes and was very straight up about my short experience, but a relatively small agency decided to give me a shot and I learned so much with them while honestly being very generously compensated for my lack of experience.  So I think the take aways are: Find a niche Dont oversell yourself, be honest And go for companies that are willing to let you learn with them, this part is really a hit or miss but you'll get it eventually   Welcome to the team, and best of luck in your journey!

The problem is I don't think it's very financially viable.  The best way I can think of doing this, there might be others, is to build a crawler which browses the web, and like I said, just reports on bad responses.   This isn't difficult or expensive, matter of fact a lot of people and companies do this sort of things for various reasons. The problem is that by pure statistics, the number of sites you will find is limited. Out of those, a number will be false positives, temporary downtimes, etc\xe2\x80\xa6 Out of the small percentage of websites you visit which are genuinely out, only a few will be business,  so yeah. Which you use to apply to the course of your liking. Few tips if you want them: Talk to the ministry of education and ask for help, they did a great deal for me, alternatively if you're still in Ireland, check in with the embassy. Also, I don't know your situation but my honest advice is, get your degree in Ireland.
